                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d789">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51/806</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Phillips</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-05-17">May 17,
                            1933</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I discussed this matter with the President this afternoon. He agrees entirely
                    that it would be wise to have the personnel appointed by outside associations
                    and so avoid giving the impression in foreign countries that the personnel
                    represented the Government of the United States. He did say, however, that the
                    salaries and fees of the personnel should be approved by the Trade Commission. I
                    told him that word had got about that he was beginning to favor Senator
                    Johnson’s amendment,<note n="2" xml:id="d789fn2">The amendment was passed as
                        Title II of the Securities Act of 1933, 48 Stat. 74, 92.</note> which
                    allegation he denied explicitly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
